inference:
The graphs of $y=f(x)$ and $y=g(x)$ do not intersect if and only if the equation $f(x)=g(x)$ has no real solutions.  This equation is
\[x^2 + 2bx + 1 = 2a(x + b).\]Then $x^2 + (2b - 2a) x + (1 - 2ab) = 0.$  This quadratic has no real roots if and only if its discriminant is negative:
\[(2b - 2a)^2 - 4(1 - 2ab) < 0.\]This simplifies to $4a^2 - 4b^2 + 8ab - 4 < 0,$ or $a^2 - b^2 + 2ab - 1 < 0.$  We can factor this as $(a + b - 1)(a - b + 1) < 0.$

The inequality $(a + b - 1)(a - b + 1) < 0$ holds if and only if exactly one of the factors is positive and the other is negative.  Thus, either
\[a + b - 1 > 0 \quad \text{and} \quad a - b + 1 < 0\]or
\[a + b - 1 < 0 \quad \text{and} \quad a - b + 1 > 0.\]The first system of inequalities is equivalent to $a > b - 1$ and $a < b - 1,$ which has no solutions.  The second system of inequalities is equivalent to $a < b - 1$ and $a > b - 1,$ which is the region between the lines $a = b - 1$ and $a = b - 1,$ which is a vertical strip of width 2.

[asy]
unitsize(1 cm);

pair moo (real t) {
  return((t,t - 1));
}

pair foo (real t) {
  return((t,t - 1));
}

real t;

draw(graph(moo,-2,2),red);
draw(graph(foo,-2,2),red);
draw((-2,0)--(2,0));
draw((0,-2)--(0,2));

label("$a = b - 1$", (2,1), E, UnFill);
label("$a = b - 1$", (2,-1), E, UnFill);

fill((1,-2)--(1,2)--(-1,2)--(-1,-2)--cycle,gray(0.7));
[/asy]

The area of this strip is $2 \cdot 2 = \boxed{4}.$

